  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of Multisectoral Lifesaving Assistance for Flood-Affected population in Bentiu and Rubkona</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The main objective of this project is to provide early action assistance in the water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH), shelter, camp coordination and camp management (CCCM) and health sectors to mitigate the compounding effects of projected severe flooding on vulnerable communities in the Bentiu camp for internally displaced people and surrounding areas in Rubkona county in Unity State. This IOM project equips and operates static and mobile clinics to provide lifesaving healthcare services, distributes cash and shelter materials in support of at-risk communities, ensures sufficient amounts of safe drinking water are available throughout the rainy season, and secures dry camp sites against future flooding to prevent displacement, among others. The project provides WASH assistance to 96,126 people, including 22,109 men, 23,070 women, 25,954 boys, 24,993 girls, and 14,419 people with disabilities, shelter assistance to 87,000 people, including 18,970 men, 18,588 women, 24,316 boys, 25,126 girls, and 13,050 people with disabilities, camp management services to 142,330 people, 32,649 men, 29,811 women, 41,543 boys, 38,327 girls, and 14,223 people with disabilities, and healthcare support to 159,601 people, including 36,709 men, 34,034 women, 45,766 boys, 43,092 girls, and 23,940 people with disabilities.</narrative>
  </description>
